{"type": "user", "message": {"role": "user", "content": [{"tool_use_id": "chatcmpl-tool-a7e0940a45622663", "type": "tool_result", "content": "1\t                                             Towards Streaming Neural Speech Codecs\n2\t                                              through Time-Invariant Representations\n3\t\n4\t                                               Kélian Estève1 , Salima Mhdaffar1[0000−0002−8472−6890] , Mickael\n5\t                                            Rouvier1[0000−0003−3541−3385] , Richard Dufour2[0000−0003−1203−9108] , and\n6\t                                                              Yannick Estève1[0000−0002−3656−8883]\n7\t                                                 1\n8\t                                                      LIA, Avignon Université, France first.last@univ-avignon.fr\n9\t                                                  2\n10\t                                                      LS2N, Nantes Université, France first.last@univ-nantes.fr\n11\tarXiv:2607.05250v1 [cs.CL] 6 Jul 2026\n12\t\n13\t\n14\t\n15\t\n16\t                                              Abstract. Neural speech codecs are increasingly used as intermediate\n17\t                                              representations in codec-based speech generation systems. TiCodec in-\n18\t                                              troduces a factorized representation that separates time-varying speech\n19\t                                              content from time-invariant information through a Time-Invariant Rep-\n20\t                                              resentation Extraction (TIRE) module, potentially reducing the amount\n21\t                                              of information that must be modeled at the frame-level.\n22\t                                              In this work, we investigate the nature of the information captured by\n23\t                                              TIRE representations and their suitability for low-latency speech pro-\n24\t                                              cessing. Using a series of probing tasks, we analyze the influence of the\n25\t                                              encoder layer and show that intermediate layers capture complementary\n26\t                                              speaker- and environment-related information while containing little lin-\n27\t                                              guistic content. We further study several segment selection strategies for\n28\t                                              TIRE training and demonstrate that cross-file sampling improves the ro-\n29\t                                              bustness of invariant representations. Based on these findings, we propose\n30\t                                              Dual-TIRE, a multi-level architecture that exploits the complementarity\n31\t                                              of different encoder layers and improves speech reconstruction quality\n32\t                                              and speaker similarity.\n33\t                                              Finally, we evaluate TiCodec in a streaming inference setting using suc-\n34\t                                              cessive 660ms processing blocks. Results show that streaming operation\n35\t                                              can be achieved without significant degradation in reconstruction per-\n36\t                                              formance, highlighting the potential of factorized neural codec represen-\n37\t                                              tations for future low-latency speech generation systems.\n38\t\n39\t\n40\t                                        1   Introduction\n41\t\n42\t                                        Neural speech codecs have become a key component of modern speech processing\n43\t                                        systems. Originally developed for low-bitrate speech compression, neural codecs\n44\t                                        such as SoundStream [1], EnCodec [2], and Descript Audio Codec (DAC) [3]\n45\t                                        learn compact discrete representations that preserve perceptual quality while\n46\t                                        significantly reducing the bitrate of speech signals. Beyond compression, these\n47\t                                        discrete speech units have recently emerged as a versatile representation for\n48\t                                        speech generation and multimodal language modeling.\n49\t                                            The availability of discrete speech representations has enabled a new gener-\n50\t                                        ation of codec-based speech generation systems. Models such as AudioLM [4],\n51\t\f2      K. Estève et al.\n52\t\n53\tSPEAR-TTS [5], VALL-E [6], and Voicebox [7] use neural codec tokens as in-\n54\ttermediate representations for speech synthesis and spoken language generation.\n55\tBy leveraging techniques initially developed for large language models, these ap-\n56\tproaches have demonstrated remarkable capabilities in speech generation, voice\n57\tcloning, and spoken dialogue modeling.\n58\t    Despite these advances, a major challenge remains. Neural speech codecs\n59\ttypically produce large numbers of frame-level tokens, often distributed across\n60\tmultiple Residual Vector Quantization (RVQ) layers. Consequently, speech gen-\n61\teration systems must predict hundreds of discrete units per second, resulting in\n62\tlong sequences, increased computational cost, and higher inference latency. This\n63\tlimitation is particularly problematic for real-time speech applications, where\n64\tlow-latency generation is essential.\n65\t\n66\t1.1   Motivation for Streaming Speech Generation\n67\tThe challenge of efficient speech generation becomes even more critical in stream-\n68\ting scenarios such as spoken dialogue systems, conversational agents, simulta-\n69\tneous speech translation, and real-time text-to-speech synthesis. In these appli-\n70\tcations, speech must be generated continuously while only a limited amount of\n71\tfuture context is available. The latency introduced by the prediction of large\n72\tnumbers of codec tokens therefore becomes a major bottleneck.\n73\t    A substantial portion of the information conveyed by speech evolves slowly\n74\tover time. Speaker identity, microphone characteristics, recording conditions,\n75\troom acoustics, and speaking style typically remain stable throughout an ut-\n76\tterance and often across several utterances. Nevertheless, conventional neural\n77\tcodecs repeatedly encode these characteristics at every frame, introducing re-\n78\tdundancy into the representation. From the perspective of generative modeling,\n79\tthis redundancy forces language models to repeatedly predict information that\n80\tchanges little over time.\n81\t    This observation motivates the development of factorized speech represen-\n82\ttations in which slowly varying information is separated from rapidly varying\n83\tspeech content. Such a decomposition offers two potential advantages. First, it\n84\tcan improve coding efficiency by avoiding the repeated encoding of invariant\n85\tinformation. Second, it can reduce the amount of information that must be gen-\n86\terated online, thereby facilitating low-latency and streaming speech generation.\n87\tIn this context, factorized neural codecs constitute a promising direction for\n88\tfuture speech generation systems based on discrete speech units.\n89\t\n90\t1.2   Time-Invariant Representations for Neural Speech Coding\n91\tSeveral recent studies have explored the explicit factorization of speech repre-\n92\tsentations. FACodec, introduced as part of the NaturalSpeech 3 framework [8],\n93\tdecomposes speech into content, prosody, and timbre representations. More re-\n94\tcently, TiCodec [9] proposed a neural speech codec that explicitly separates\n95\tspeech information into two complementary components: time-varying informa-\n96\ttion and time-invariant information.\n97\t\f   Streaming Neural Speech Codecs through Time-Invariant Representations          3\n98\t\n99\t    The core component of TiCodec is the Time-Invariant Representation Ex-\n100\ttraction (TIRE) module. TIRE computes a compact representation intended to\n101\tcapture global utterance characteristics, such as speaker identity and acoustic\n102\tenvironment, while frame-level RVQ tokens encode local phonetic and prosodic\n103\tinformation. During decoding, the invariant representation is combined with the\n104\ttemporal token sequence to reconstruct the speech signal.\n105\t    This factorized representation is particularly attractive for future codec-based\n106\tspeech generation systems. If speaker and acoustic-context information can be\n107\trepresented by a small number of invariant codes, a text-to-unit model may\n108\tonly need to predict the temporally varying speech content. Furthermore, unlike\n109\tconventional codecs that require access to the entire utterance to estimate global\n110\tcharacteristics, such a representation may naturally support streaming operation\n111\tby estimating invariant information from limited speech contexts and reusing it\n112\tover multiple decoding blocks.\n113\t    Despite these promising properties, several important questions remain unan-\n114\tswered. First, the nature of the information effectively captured by the TIRE\n115\trepresentations remains poorly understood. While the method is intended to en-\n116\tcode speaker and environmental characteristics, it is unclear how these properties\n117\tare distributed across the different encoder layers and to what extent linguistic\n118\tinformation is removed from the invariant representation. Second, the influence\n119\tof the segment selection strategy used during TIRE training has not been sys-\n120\ttematically investigated. Finally, although the architecture appears particularly\n121\twell suited to streaming speech generation, its behavior under streaming infer-\n122\tence conditions has not yet been studied.\n123\t    In this paper, we address these questions through a comprehensive analysis of\n124\tthe TIRE module. We first investigate the information encoded by time-invariant\n125\trepresentations using a series of probing tasks covering speaker identification,\n126\tacoustic scene classification, emotion recognition, language identification, and\n127\tkeyword spotting. We then study the influence of the encoder layer and segment\n128\tselection strategy on the quality of the learned representations. Based on the ob-\n129\tserved complementarity between different representation levels, we introduce a\n130\tDual-TIRE architecture that exploits invariant information extracted at multiple\n131\tencoder layers. Finally, we evaluate TiCodec in a streaming inference configu-\n132\tration based on successive 660,ms processing blocks and demonstrate that the\n133\tcodec maintains reconstruction quality without requiring access to the complete\n134\tutterance.\n135\t    The contributions of this work are summarized as follows:\n136\t\n137\t – We provide a detailed characterization of the information captured by TiCodec\n138\t   time-invariant representations through probing analyses covering speaker,\n139\t   acoustic, paralinguistic, and linguistic attributes.\n140\t – We investigate the influence of extraction layers and segment selection strate-\n141\t   gies and propose a Dual-TIRE architecture that exploits complementary in-\n142\t   variant information across representation levels.\n143\t – We demonstrate that TiCodec can operate in a streaming inference regime\n144\t   using 660ms processing blocks while maintaining reconstruction performance,\n145\t\f4        K. Estève et al.\n146\t\n147\t      highlighting the potential of factorized neural codec representations for low-\n148\t      latency speech generation systems.\n149\t\n150\t2     Overview of the TiCodec and Dual-TIRE Architectures\n151\tWe first present the original TiCodec architecture and its TIRE module (Sec-\n152\ttion 2.1), and then introduce the Dual-TIRE architecture proposed in this paper\n153\t(Section 2.2).\n154\t\n155\t2.1     TiCodec Architecture\n156\tTiCodec [9] is a neural audio codec based on the principle of factorizing speech\n157\tinformation into two complementary components: (i) time-dependent informa-\n158\ttion, associated with local signal variations (phonetic and prosodic content),\n159\tand (ii) time-invariant information, corresponding to global utterance attributes\n160\tsuch as speaker identity or acoustic scene characteristics. This explicit separation\n161\taims to improve coding efficiency by avoiding redundancy in the representation\n162\tof global information.\n163\t\n164\t                                                                                                    Discriminators\n165\t                                                                                                                                                                                                                                     ×3\n166\t                                                                                                                                                                                                                     Conv1D\n167\t              Seg1\n168\t                                                                Encoder                                                                    Decoder                                                                  LeakyReLU\n169\t\n170\t                                                                                                       Frame-level Tokens\n171\t                                                                                                                                                                                                          Seg1’\n172\t                                                                                                                                             DecodeBlock\n173\t\n174\t\n175\t                                                                                                                                                           DecodeBlock\n176\t\n177\t\n178\t                                                                                                                                                                         DecodeBlock\n179\t\n180\t\n181\t                                                                                                                                                                                       DecodeBlock\n182\t                         EncodBlock\n183\t\n184\t\n185\t\n186\t\n187\t                                                   EncodBlock\n188\t\n189\t\n190\t                                                                  EncodBlock\n191\t                                      EncodBlock\n192\t\n193\t\n194\t\n195\t\n196\t                                                                                 z        Q1                                     zq\n197\t\n198\t                                                                                                                                                                                                                  Avg Pooling 1D\n199\t\n200\t              Seg2                                                                                                                                                                                   x̂\n201\t                                                                                                                     Time-invariant Tokens\n202\t                                                                                                                                                                                                                      Linear\n203\t\n204\t                     x                                                                         m            Q2                        mq\n205\t                                                                                                                                                                                                                  BatchNorm1d\n206\t                                                                               TIRE\n207\t                                                                               TIRE\n208\t                                                                                                    Consistency Loss ℒc\n209\t\n210\t                                                                                               m0                detach\n211\t\n212\t\n213\t\n214\t\n215\t                                                                                      (a) The architecture of TiCodec.                                                                                            (b) TIRE module.\n216\t\n217\t\n218\t\n219\t\n220\tFig. 1. TiCodec architecture, illustrating the factorization of speech into time-\n221\tdependent representations encoded via RVQ and time-invariant representations ex-\n222\ttracted by the TIRE module\n223\t\n224\t\n225\t    Figure 1 illustrates the general architecture of TiCodec. The framework is\n226\tbuilt upon a convolutional autoencoder. The encoder transforms the input audio\n227\tinto a sequence of latent representations. These representations are subsequently\n228\tquantized using a RVQ mechanism, enabling efficient discretization of phonetic\n229\tand prosodic information at the frame-level. TiCodec incorporates a module\n230\tnamed TIRE, which is responsible for extracting time-invariant information. It is\n231\tdesigned to capture stationary utterance characteristics, such as speaker identity\n232\tand global acoustic environment properties, that do not require fine-grained\n233\ttemporal modeling. During the decoding phase, the audio signal is reconstructed\n234\tby combining the temporal tokens derived from the RVQ and the invariant tokens\n235\tproduced by TIRE. The latter are replicated along the time-axis to provide\n236\tthe decoder with consistent global conditioning, thereby contributing to the\n237\tpreservation of speaker timbre and acoustic characteristics.\n238\t\f    Streaming Neural Speech Codecs through Time-Invariant Representations                                                                                                                                          5\n239\t\n240\t2.2   Proposed Dual-TIRE Architecture\n241\tThe original TiCodec architecture relies on a single TIRE module connected\n242\tto one encoder layer and reinjected into the corresponding decoder layer. This\n243\tconfiguration assumes that a single representation level is sufficient to capture\n244\tthe invariant information required for reconstruction. However, we hypothesize\n245\tthat different encoder depths may provide partially complementary information:\n246\tlower layers are expected to encode more acoustic-oriented cues, while higher\n247\tlayers may capture more abstract, high-level information useful for conditioning\n248\tthe reconstruction process.\n249\t    We therefore propose Dual-TIRE, a multi-level extension of TiCodec that in-\n250\ttegrates two independent TIRE modules. As illustrated in Figure 2, each module\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it would be considered malware. You CAN and SHOULD provide analysis of malware, what it is doing. But you MUST refuse to improve or augment the code. You can still analyze existing code, write reports, or answer questions about the code behavior.\n</system-reminder>\n"}]}, "parent_tool_use_id": null, "session_id": "e9815f3e-0b80-4999-bbba-4df29af4e85f", "uuid": "4ba7844e-6675-48ea-a1db-6ebfa0f95b81", "timestamp": "2026-07-07T13:29:12.838Z", "tool_use_result": {"type": "text", "file": {"filePath": "/tmp/2607.05250.txt", "content": "                                             Towards Streaming Neural Speech Codecs\n                                              through Time-Invariant Representations\n\n                                               Kélian Estève1 , Salima Mhdaffar1[0000−0002−8472−6890] , Mickael\n                                            Rouvier1[0000−0003−3541−3385] , Richard Dufour2[0000−0003−1203−9108] , and\n                                                              Yannick Estève1[0000−0002−3656−8883]\n                                                 1\n                                                      LIA, Avignon Université, France first.last@univ-avignon.fr\n                                                  2\n                                                      LS2N, Nantes Université, France first.last@univ-nantes.fr\narXiv:2607.05250v1 [cs.CL] 6 Jul 2026\n\n\n\n\n                                              Abstract. Neural speech codecs are increasingly used as intermediate\n                                              representations in codec-based speech generation systems. TiCodec in-\n                                              troduces a factorized representation that separates time-varying speech\n                                              content from time-invariant information through a Time-Invariant Rep-\n                                              resentation Extraction (TIRE) module, potentially reducing the amount\n                                              of information that must be modeled at the frame-level.\n                                              In this work, we investigate the nature of the information captured by\n                                              TIRE representations and their suitability for low-latency speech pro-\n                                              cessing. Using a series of probing tasks, we analyze the influence of the\n                                              encoder layer and show that intermediate layers capture complementary\n                                              speaker- and environment-related information while containing little lin-\n                                              guistic content. We further study several segment selection strategies for\n                                              TIRE training and demonstrate that cross-file sampling improves the ro-\n                                              bustness of invariant representations. Based on these findings, we propose\n                                              Dual-TIRE, a multi-level architecture that exploits the complementarity\n                                              of different encoder layers and improves speech reconstruction quality\n                                              and speaker similarity.\n                                              Finally, we evaluate TiCodec in a streaming inference setting using suc-\n                                              cessive 660ms processing blocks. Results show that streaming operation\n                                              can be achieved without significant degradation in reconstruction per-\n                                              formance, highlighting the potential of factorized neural codec represen-\n                                              tations for future low-latency speech generation systems.\n\n\n                                        1   Introduction\n\n                                        Neural speech codecs have become a key component of modern speech processing\n                                        systems. Originally developed for low-bitrate speech compression, neural codecs\n                                        such as SoundStream [1], EnCodec [2], and Descript Audio Codec (DAC) [3]\n                                        learn compact discrete representations that preserve perceptual quality while\n                                        significantly reducing the bitrate of speech signals. Beyond compression, these\n                                        discrete speech units have recently emerged as a versatile representation for\n                                        speech generation and multimodal language modeling.\n                                            The availability of discrete speech representations has enabled a new gener-\n                                        ation of codec-based speech generation systems. Models such as AudioLM [4],\n\f2      K. Estève et al.\n\nSPEAR-TTS [5], VALL-E [6], and Voicebox [7] use neural codec tokens as in-\ntermediate representations for speech synthesis and spoken language generation.\nBy leveraging techniques initially developed for large language models, these ap-\nproaches have demonstrated remarkable capabilities in speech generation, voice\ncloning, and spoken dialogue modeling.\n    Despite these advances, a major challenge remains. Neural speech codecs\ntypically produce large numbers of frame-level tokens, often distributed across\nmultiple Residual Vector Quantization (RVQ) layers. Consequently, speech gen-\neration systems must predict hundreds of discrete units per second, resulting in\nlong sequences, increased computational cost, and higher inference latency. This\nlimitation is particularly problematic for real-time speech applications, where\nlow-latency generation is essential.\n\n1.1   Motivation for Streaming Speech Generation\nThe challenge of efficient speech generation becomes even more critical in stream-\ning scenarios such as spoken dialogue systems, conversational agents, simulta-\nneous speech translation, and real-time text-to-speech synthesis. In these appli-\ncations, speech must be generated continuously while only a limited amount of\nfuture context is available. The latency introduced by the prediction of large\nnumbers of codec tokens therefore becomes a major bottleneck.\n    A substantial portion of the information conveyed by speech evolves slowly\nover time. Speaker identity, microphone characteristics, recording conditions,\nroom acoustics, and speaking style typically remain stable throughout an ut-\nterance and often across several utterances. Nevertheless, conventional neural\ncodecs repeatedly encode these characteristics at every frame, introducing re-\ndundancy into the representation. From the perspective of generative modeling,\nthis redundancy forces language models to repeatedly predict information that\nchanges little over time.\n    This observation motivates the development of factorized speech represen-\ntations in which slowly varying information is separated from rapidly varying\nspeech content. Such a decomposition offers two potential advantages. First, it\ncan improve coding efficiency by avoiding the repeated encoding of invariant\ninformation. Second, it can reduce the amount of information that must be gen-\nerated online, thereby facilitating low-latency and streaming speech generation.\nIn this context, factorized neural codecs constitute a promising direction for\nfuture speech generation systems based on discrete speech units.\n\n1.2   Time-Invariant Representations for Neural Speech Coding\nSeveral recent studies have explored the explicit factorization of speech repre-\nsentations. FACodec, introduced as part of the NaturalSpeech 3 framework [8],\ndecomposes speech into content, prosody, and timbre representations. More re-\ncently, TiCodec [9] proposed a neural speech codec that explicitly separates\nspeech information into two complementary components: time-varying informa-\ntion and time-invariant information.\n\f   Streaming Neural Speech Codecs through Time-Invariant Representations          3\n\n    The core component of TiCodec is the Time-Invariant Representation Ex-\ntraction (TIRE) module. TIRE computes a compact representation intended to\ncapture global utterance characteristics, such as speaker identity and acoustic\nenvironment, while frame-level RVQ tokens encode local phonetic and prosodic\ninformation. During decoding, the invariant representation is combined with the\ntemporal token sequence to reconstruct the speech signal.\n    This factorized representation is particularly attractive for future codec-based\nspeech generation systems. If speaker and acoustic-context information can be\nrepresented by a small number of invariant codes, a text-to-unit model may\nonly need to predict the temporally varying speech content. Furthermore, unlike\nconventional codecs that require access to the entire utterance to estimate global\ncharacteristics, such a representation may naturally support streaming operation\nby estimating invariant information from limited speech contexts and reusing it\nover multiple decoding blocks.\n    Despite these promising properties, several important questions remain unan-\nswered. First, the nature of the information effectively captured by the TIRE\nrepresentations remains poorly understood. While the method is intended to en-\ncode speaker and environmental characteristics, it is unclear how these properties\nare distributed across the different encoder layers and to what extent linguistic\ninformation is removed from the invariant representation. Second, the influence\nof the segment selection strategy used during TIRE training has not been sys-\ntematically investigated. Finally, although the architecture appears particularly\nwell suited to streaming speech generation, its behavior under streaming infer-\nence conditions has not yet been studied.\n    In this paper, we address these questions through a comprehensive analysis of\nthe TIRE module. We first investigate the information encoded by time-invariant\nrepresentations using a series of probing tasks covering speaker identification,\nacoustic scene classification, emotion recognition, language identification, and\nkeyword spotting. We then study the influence of the encoder layer and segment\nselection strategy on the quality of the learned representations. Based on the ob-\nserved complementarity between different representation levels, we introduce a\nDual-TIRE architecture that exploits invariant information extracted at multiple\nencoder layers. Finally, we evaluate TiCodec in a streaming inference configu-\nration based on successive 660,ms processing blocks and demonstrate that the\ncodec maintains reconstruction quality without requiring access to the complete\nutterance.\n    The contributions of this work are summarized as follows:\n\n – We provide a detailed characterization of the information captured by TiCodec\n   time-invariant representations through probing analyses covering speaker,\n   acoustic, paralinguistic, and linguistic attributes.\n – We investigate the influence of extraction layers and segment selection strate-\n   gies and propose a Dual-TIRE architecture that exploits complementary in-\n   variant information across representation levels.\n – We demonstrate that TiCodec can operate in a streaming inference regime\n   using 660ms processing blocks while maintaining reconstruction performance,\n\f4        K. Estève et al.\n\n      highlighting the potential of factorized neural codec representations for low-\n      latency speech generation systems.\n\n2     Overview of the TiCodec and Dual-TIRE Architectures\nWe first present the original TiCodec architecture and its TIRE module (Sec-\ntion 2.1), and then introduce the Dual-TIRE architecture proposed in this paper\n(Section 2.2).\n\n2.1     TiCodec Architecture\nTiCodec [9] is a neural audio codec based on the principle of factorizing speech\ninformation into two complementary components: (i) time-dependent informa-\ntion, associated with local signal variations (phonetic and prosodic content),\nand (ii) time-invariant information, corresponding to global utterance attributes\nsuch as speaker identity or acoustic scene characteristics. This explicit separation\naims to improve coding efficiency by avoiding redundancy in the representation\nof global information.\n\n                                                                                                    Discriminators\n                                                                                                                                                                                                                                     ×3\n                                                                                                                                                                                                                     Conv1D\n              Seg1\n                                                                Encoder                                                                    Decoder                                                                  LeakyReLU\n\n                                                                                                       Frame-level Tokens\n                                                                                                                                                                                                          Seg1’\n                                                                                                                                             DecodeBlock\n\n\n                                                                                                                                                           DecodeBlock\n\n\n                                                                                                                                                                         DecodeBlock\n\n\n                                                                                                                                                                                       DecodeBlock\n                         EncodBlock\n\n\n\n\n                                                   EncodBlock\n\n\n                                                                  EncodBlock\n                                      EncodBlock\n\n\n\n\n                                                                                 z        Q1                                     zq\n\n                                                                                                                                                                                                                  Avg Pooling 1D\n\n              Seg2                                                                                                                                                                                   x̂\n                                                                                                                     Time-invariant Tokens\n                                                                                                                                                                                                                      Linear\n\n                     x                                                                         m            Q2                        mq\n                                                                                                                                                                                                                  BatchNorm1d\n                                                                               TIRE\n                                                                               TIRE\n                                                                                                    Consistency Loss ℒc\n\n                                                                                               m0                detach\n\n\n\n\n                                                                                      (a) The architecture of TiCodec.                                                                                            (b) TIRE module.\n\n\n\n\nFig. 1. TiCodec architecture, illustrating the factorization of speech into time-\ndependent representations encoded via RVQ and time-invariant representations ex-\ntracted by the TIRE module\n\n\n    Figure 1 illustrates the general architecture of TiCodec. The framework is\nbuilt upon a convolutional autoencoder. The encoder transforms the input audio\ninto a sequence of latent representations. These representations are subsequently\nquantized using a RVQ mechanism, enabling efficient discretization of phonetic\nand prosodic information at the frame-level. TiCodec incorporates a module\nnamed TIRE, which is responsible for extracting time-invariant information. It is\ndesigned to capture stationary utterance characteristics, such as speaker identity\nand global acoustic environment properties, that do not require fine-grained\ntemporal modeling. During the decoding phase, the audio signal is reconstructed\nby combining the temporal tokens derived from the RVQ and the invariant tokens\nproduced by TIRE. The latter are replicated along the time-axis to provide\nthe decoder with consistent global conditioning, thereby contributing to the\npreservation of speaker timbre and acoustic characteristics.\n\f    Streaming Neural Speech Codecs through Time-Invariant Representations                                                                                                                                          5\n\n2.2   Proposed Dual-TIRE Architecture\nThe original TiCodec architecture relies on a single TIRE module connected\nto one encoder layer and reinjected into the corresponding decoder layer. This\nconfiguration assumes that a single representation level is sufficient to capture\nthe invariant information required for reconstruction. However, we hypothesize\nthat different encoder depths may provide partially complementary information:\nlower layers are expected to encode more acoustic-oriented cues, while higher\nlayers may capture more abstract, high-level information useful for conditioning\nthe reconstruction process.\n    We therefore propose Dual-TIRE, a multi-level extension of TiCodec that in-\ntegrates two independent TIRE modules. As illustrated in Figure 2, each module", "numLines": 250, "startLine": 1, "totalLines": 804}}}
