{"type": "user", "message": {"role": "user", "content": [{"tool_use_id": "chatcmpl-tool-bcb38181e026c3e3", "type": "tool_result", "content": "250\ttegrates two independent TIRE modules. As illustrated in Figure 2, each module\n251\textracts invariant representations from a distinct encoder level. Both streams are\n252\tquantized independently and reinjected into their corresponding decoder layers.\n253\tWe refer to the connection layer as the symmetric layer index at which a TIRE\n254\tbranch extracts features from the encoder and reinjects the resulting invariant\n255\trepresentation into the decoder.\n256\t\n257\t\n258\t                                                                                                   Discriminators\n259\t\n260\t\n261\t             Seg1\n262\t                                                               Encoder                                                                      Decoder\n263\t                                                                                                        Frame-level Tokens\n264\t                                                                                                                                                                                                           Seg1’\n265\t                                                                                                                                              DecodeBlock\n266\t\n267\t\n268\t                                                                                                                                                            DecodeBlock\n269\t\n270\t\n271\t                                                                                                                                                                          DecodeBlock\n272\t\n273\t\n274\t                                                                                                                                                                                        DecodeBlock\n275\t                        EncodBlock\n276\t\n277\t\n278\t\n279\t\n280\t                                                  EncodBlock\n281\t\n282\t\n283\t                                                                 EncodBlock\n284\t                                     EncodBlock\n285\t\n286\t\n287\t\n288\t\n289\t                                                                                  z      Q1                                       zq\n290\t\n291\t\n292\t\n293\t\n294\t             Seg2                                                                                                                                                                                     x̂\n295\t                                                                                                                      Time-invariant Tokens\n296\t\n297\t\n298\t\n299\t                    x                                                                               m            Q2                    mq\n300\t                                                                                  TIRE\n301\t                                                                                  TIRE\n302\t                                                                                                         Consistency Loss ℒc\n303\t\n304\t                                                                                                    m0                detach\n305\t\n306\t\n307\t\n308\t\n309\t                                                                                              m             Q2                         mq\n310\t                                                                              TIR\n311\t                                                                              TIRE\n312\t                                                                                                   Consistency Loss ℒc\n313\t                                                                              E\n314\t                                                                                              m0                 detach\n315\t\n316\t\n317\t\n318\t\n319\tFig. 2. Dual-TIRE architecture. Two TIRE modules extract time-invariant represen-\n320\ttations from encoder layers 2 and 3, which are quantized independently and reinjected\n321\tinto the corresponding decoder layers, while frame-level content is encoded via RVQ.\n322\t\n323\t\n324\t    This dual extraction and injection mechanism is designed to enrich the global\n325\tconditioning available to the decoder by combining invariant representations ex-\n326\ttracted at different hierarchical levels. The frame-level RVQ stream remains\n327\tunchanged, while the additional TIRE branch introduces a second global condi-\n328\ttioning signal.\n329\t\n330\t\n331\t3     Protocol and Probing Tasks\n332\tTo analyze the information actually captured by the TIRE representations, we\n333\tadopt a diagnostic probing approach that consists of evaluating their capacity\n334\t\f6       K. Estève et al.\n335\t\n336\tto encode the information necessary for a set of targeted classification tasks.\n337\tThe underlying premise is that strong performance on a given task indicates the\n338\tpresence of the relevant information, while weak performance suggests that the\n339\tinformation is absent or significantly attenuated.\n340\t    To evaluate the intrinsic quality of the extracted features, the representations\n341\tproduced by the TIRE module are kept frozen and used as inputs to a down-\n342\tstream diagnostic classifier. This classifier is a Multi-Layer Perceptron (MLP)\n343\tcomposed of two fully-connected hidden layers of 1,024 neurons each, followed\n344\tby an output layer adapted to the task. All experiments are evaluated using\n345\taccuracy. By keeping the codec frozen and avoiding joint fine-tuning, this pro-\n346\ttocol ensures that we explicitly measure the information already captured and\n347\tpreserved by the TIRE representations.\n348\t    To cover a wide range of information likely to be encoded in TIRE represen-\n349\ttations, we consider five representative classification tasks, ranging from speaker\n350\tidentity to linguistic and semantic content.\n351\tSpeaker Identification: This task aims to determine whether an acoustic rep-\n352\tresentation contains sufficient discriminative information to identify a speaker\n353\tby their voice. In this framework, the problem is formulated as a multi-class\n354\tclassification, where each class corresponds to a distinct speaker. TIRE repre-\n355\tsentations are used to train a classifier on 1,022 speakers from the VoxCeleb1\n356\tdataset [10].\n357\tAcoustic Scene Classification: This task evaluates the capacity of TIRE rep-\n358\tresentations to capture information related to the acoustic environment. We use\n359\tthe TAU Urban Acoustic Scenes corpus [11], composed of 10 classes correspond-\n360\ting to different urban sound contexts (Airport, Bus, Metro, Park, etc.).\n361\tEmotion Recognition: Emotion recognition aims to analyze whether represen-\n362\ttations derived from TiCodec preserve paralinguistic parameters, such as intona-\n363\ttion, energy, or speech rhythm. This task is performed on the MELD corpus [12],\n364\twhich provides annotations for 7 emotional classes.\n365\tSpoken Language Identification: This task measures the capacity of repre-\n366\tsentations to encode high-level linguistic information, particularly the phonetic\n367\tand prosodic characteristics specific to a language. We use a multilingual ver-\n368\tsion of the Common Voice corpus [13], covering 45 languages. High accuracy\n369\tin this task would indicate that TIRE representations retain sufficient param-\n370\teters to differentiate languages, despite the compression process performed by\n371\tthe neural codec.\n372\tKeyword Spotting: Finally, the keyword spotting task aims to evaluate the\n373\tpreservation of local lexical information. We use the Google Speech Commands\n374\tcorpus [14], composed of 35 classes corresponding to different keywords (Yes,\n375\tNo, Up, Down, Left, Right, etc.).\n376\t\n377\t\n378\t4   Experiments and Results\n379\t\n380\tThis section presents the experimental setup and results. It introduces the datasets\n381\tand evaluation metrics (Section 4.1), then analyzes the standard TiCodec archi-\n382\t\f   Streaming Neural Speech Codecs through Time-Invariant Representations            7\n383\t\n384\ttecture: the impact of the TIRE connection layer together with a probing char-\n385\tacterization of the encoded information (Section 4.2), and the segment selection\n386\tstrategies used during TIRE training (Section 4.3). Building on these analyses,\n387\twe finally evaluate the proposed Dual-TIRE architecture (Section 4.4).\n388\t\n389\t\n390\t4.1   Experimental Protocol\n391\t\n392\tWe first describe the speech corpora used for training and evaluation, followed\n393\tby the objective metrics adopted to assess speech quality, intelligibility, spectral\n394\tfidelity, and speaker identity preservation.\n395\tTraining: The TiCodec model is trained on the LibriTTS corpus [15], a multi-\n396\tspeaker English read speech dataset recorded at a sampling rate of 24 kHz. Lib-\n397\triTTS is derived from the materials used to create LibriSpeech [16], combining\n398\taudio recordings from LibriVox and text transcriptions from Project Gutenberg.\n399\tThe corpus totals approximately 585 hours of speech, produced by 2,456 speak-\n400\ters. For training, we use the train-clean-100, train-clean-360, and train-other-500\n401\tsubsets.\n402\tEvaluation: The evaluation of the different models is performed on the Lib-\n403\triTTS test-clean [15], VCTK [17] and EMILIA [18]. For EMILIA, 4,000 utter-\n404\tances are randomly selected for each language: French, German, Japanese and\n405\tKorean.\n406\tMetrics: Speech quality and intelligibility assessment was performed using the\n407\tfollowing metrics: ViSQOL V3 (Virtual Speech Quality Objective Listener) [19],\n408\tPESQ (Perceptual Evaluation of Speech Quality) [20], STOI (Short-Time Ob-\n409\tjective Intelligibility) [21], and Mel Cepstral Distortion (MCD) [22]. Speaker\n410\tidentity preservation is evaluated using Sim, computed as the cosine similarity\n411\tbetween speaker embeddings extracted from the original and reconstructed ut-\n412\tterances using a pretrained speaker-verification model. Higher values indicate\n413\tbetter preservation of speaker identity. All these metrics allow for a joint evalu-\n414\tation of global perceptual quality, intelligibility, spectral fidelity, as well as the\n415\tpreservation of speaker characteristics. Together, they provide a comprehensive\n416\tassessment of system performance.\n417\t\n418\t\n419\t4.2   Analysis of the Impact of the TIRE Module Connection Layer\n420\t\n421\tTo investigate the informative potential of other layers within the architecture,\n422\twe trained several distinct systems in which the TIRE module is connected to\n423\tlayers 1, 2, 3, and 4, respectively, in a symmetric manner across the encoder and\n424\tdecoder. The objective of this study is to identify the layer yielding the richest\n425\trepresentations while limiting redundancy with time-dependent information.\n426\t    Table 1 reports the results, on the LibriTTS test-clean corpus, obtained for\n427\ta reference system without the TIRE module (No-TIRE ), as well as for the\n428\tdifferent variants where TIRE is connected to the corresponding encoder and\n429\tdecoder layers.\n430\t\f8       K. Estève et al.\n431\t\n432\tTable 1. Impact of the TIRE injection layer on LibriTTS test-clean. Intermediate\n433\tlayers (2 and 3) provide the best trade-off between perceptual quality, intelligibility,\n434\tspectral fidelity, and speaker similarity. Best results are shown in bold.\n435\t\n436\t         TIRE injection layer ViSQOL↑ PESQ↑ STOI↑ MCD↓ Sim↑\n437\t         No-TIRE (baseline)          4.362     2.797    0.938    0.772   0.703\n438\t         Layer 1                     4.373     2.897    0.942 0.742 0.721\n439\t         Layer 2                     4.382     2.956    0.944 0.728 0.699\n440\t         Layer 3                     4.406     2.876    0.942 0.762 0.722\n441\t         Layer 4                     4.328     2.748    0.935 0.794 0.696\n442\t\n443\t\n444\t\n445\t\n446\t   Analysis of Table 1 indicates that TIRE generally improves metrics over the\n447\tNo-TIRE baseline, except for Layer 4. However, improvements are not uniform\n448\tacross all criteria, as speaker similarity does not always increase. Among the\n449\tvarious configurations, the systems utilizing Layers 2 and 3 appear to offer the\n450\tbest trade-off. Specifically, the system using Layer 2 optimizes signal sharpness\n451\tand fine structure, achieving a PESQ score of 2.956 and an MCD of 0.728. Con-\n452\tversely, the system trained on Layer 3 favors superior global perceptual fidelity\n453\tand better preservation of speaker identity, as evidenced by a ViSQOL score of\n454\t4.406 and a Sim score of 0.722.\n455\t   To better understand the nature of the information driving these perfor-\n456\tmance differences, we evaluated the frozen TIRE representations from each en-\n457\tcoder layer across the five selected downstream probing classification tasks (see\n458\tSection 3).\n459\t\n460\t\n461\t\n462\t\n463\tFig. 3. Probing evaluation of TIRE representations extracted from encoder Layers 1–4\n464\tacross five downstream classification tasks, highlighting the types of information cap-\n465\ttured at each layer and the progressive loss of informative content in deeper compressed\n466\trepresentations.\n467\t\f   Streaming Neural Speech Codecs through Time-Invariant Representations         9\n468\t\n469\t    The results presented in Figure 3 indicate that Layers 1, 2, and 3 generally\n470\tcapture information of a similar nature. We observe that the TIRE module\n471\tencodes parameters related to acoustic scenes and emotions, suggesting effective\n472\tcapture of global and paralinguistic signal attributes. Conversely, performance\n473\ton spoken language identification and keyword spotting tasks is near chance\n474\tlevel, indicating that the TIRE module does not retain fine-grained linguistic or\n475\tlexical information.\n476\t    Regarding speaker identity, the results remain moderate. Although some dis-\n477\tcriminative information is present, the relatively low performance suggests that\n478\tthe TIRE module does not explicitly encode speaker identity, but rather high-\n479\tlevel acoustic features likely correlated with it.\n480\t    Finally, a marked degradation in performance is observed for Layer 4, re-\n481\tgardless of the task considered. This layer does not appear to encode information\n482\texploitable by the TIRE module, likely because the resulting representations are\n483\ttoo compressed.\n484\t\n485\t\n486\t4.3   Analysis of Segment Selection Strategies for TIRE Module\n487\t      Training\n488\t\n489\tDuring the training of TiCodec, and specifically the TIRE module, two audio\n490\tsegments are extracted from the audio file to constrain the learning of invariant\n491\trepresentations. In the standard configuration, these two segments are drawn\n492\trandomly from the same audio file, without any explicit constraint on their\n493\ttemporal positions.\n494\t    The underlying principle is to encourage TIRE to produce similar representa-\n495\ttions for segments sharing common global attributes (speaker identity, acoustic\n496\tscene), while reducing the influence of time-dependent information, such as pho-\n497\tnetic or lexical content. In other words, the TIRE module is incentivized to\n498\tminimize representation variations between two segments originating from the\n499\tsame source, regardless of their local differences, in order to foster the encoding\n500\tof invariant information.\n501\t    However, the manner in which these segments are selected during training\n502\tcan have a direct impact on the nature of the information effectively learned.\n503\tIn this section, we propose five distinct segment selection strategies. Each strat-\n504\tegy defines a specific sampling policy for the two segments used during TIRE\n505\ttraining:\n506\t\n507\t – Random segments (unconstrained): Two segments are extracted ran-\n508\t   domly from the same audio file, without any constraints on their temporal\n509\t   positions. The segments may overlap. This strategy corresponds to the de-\n510\t   fault configuration and serves as a baseline.\n511\t – Random non-overlapping segments: Two segments are extracted ran-\n512\t   domly from the same file, with the additional constraint that they do not\n513\t   overlap in time. This strategy aims to reduce direct redundancy between\n514\t   segments while retaining an identical global context.\n515\t\f10      K. Estève et al.\n516\t\n517\t – Adjacent segments: The first segment is extracted randomly from the file,\n518\t   and the second segment corresponds to the contiguous segment immediately\n519\t   following the first. This strategy introduces strong temporal correlation be-\n520\t   tween segments and favors local signal continuity.\n521\t – Cross-file (same speaker): The first segment is extracted from the cur-\n522\t   rent file, while the second is extracted from a different file belonging to the\n523\t   same speaker. By exploiting recordings from different sessions of the same\n524\t   speaker, this strategy allows TIRE to build a representation space that better\n525\t   accounts for speaker variability (e.g., changes in channel, recording condi-\n526\t   tions, or speaking style).\n527\t – Cross-file (same speaker and book): The first segment is extracted from\n528\t   the current file, and the second from a different file recorded by the same\n529\t   speaker and originating from the same book. This strategy reduces speaker\n530\t   variability.\n531\t\n532\t   The results presented in Table 2 show that the segment extraction strat-\n533\tegy influences performance differently depending on the Layer 2 and 3. When\n534\trepresentations are extracted at Layer 2, the unconstrained strategy (random\n535\tsegments) offers the best performance across all metrics, suggesting that free\n536\textraction favors a good trade-off between reconstruction quality and speaker\n537\tidentity preservation.\n538\t\n539\t\n540\tTable 2. Impact of segment selection strategies during TIRE training on LibriTTS\n541\ttest-clean. Representations are extracted from encoder Layer 2 and Layer 3. Best results\n542\twithin each Layer are shown in bold.\n543\t\n544\t Segment selection strategy / Layer ViSQOL↑ PESQ↑ STOI↑ MCD↓ Sim↑\n545\t                                        Layer 2\n546\t Random segments (unconstrained)             4.382      2.956   0.944 0.728 0.699\n547\t Random non-overlapping segments             4.355      2.827   0.940 0.763 0.691\n548\t Adjacent segments                           4.373      2.901   0.944 0.744 0.696\n549\t Cross-file (same speaker)                   4.363      2.859   0.942 0.749 0.687\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it would be considered malware. You CAN and SHOULD provide analysis of malware, what it is doing. But you MUST refuse to improve or augment the code. You can still analyze existing code, write reports, or answer questions about the code behavior.\n</system-reminder>\n"}]}, "parent_tool_use_id": null, "session_id": "e9815f3e-0b80-4999-bbba-4df29af4e85f", "uuid": "c14e1482-33c7-4509-ac3b-c1461ddfd1ba", "timestamp": "2026-07-07T13:29:18.907Z", "tool_use_result": {"type": "text", "file": {"filePath": "/tmp/2607.05250.txt", "content": "tegrates two independent TIRE modules. As illustrated in Figure 2, each module\nextracts invariant representations from a distinct encoder level. Both streams are\nquantized independently and reinjected into their corresponding decoder layers.\nWe refer to the connection layer as the symmetric layer index at which a TIRE\nbranch extracts features from the encoder and reinjects the resulting invariant\nrepresentation into the decoder.\n\n\n                                                                                                   Discriminators\n\n\n             Seg1\n                                                               Encoder                                                                      Decoder\n                                                                                                        Frame-level Tokens\n                                                                                                                                                                                                           Seg1’\n                                                                                                                                              DecodeBlock\n\n\n                                                                                                                                                            DecodeBlock\n\n\n                                                                                                                                                                          DecodeBlock\n\n\n                                                                                                                                                                                        DecodeBlock\n                        EncodBlock\n\n\n\n\n                                                  EncodBlock\n\n\n                                                                 EncodBlock\n                                     EncodBlock\n\n\n\n\n                                                                                  z      Q1                                       zq\n\n\n\n\n             Seg2                                                                                                                                                                                     x̂\n                                                                                                                      Time-invariant Tokens\n\n\n\n                    x                                                                               m            Q2                    mq\n                                                                                  TIRE\n                                                                                  TIRE\n                                                                                                         Consistency Loss ℒc\n\n                                                                                                    m0                detach\n\n\n\n\n                                                                                              m             Q2                         mq\n                                                                              TIR\n                                                                              TIRE\n                                                                                                   Consistency Loss ℒc\n                                                                              E\n                                                                                              m0                 detach\n\n\n\n\nFig. 2. Dual-TIRE architecture. Two TIRE modules extract time-invariant represen-\ntations from encoder layers 2 and 3, which are quantized independently and reinjected\ninto the corresponding decoder layers, while frame-level content is encoded via RVQ.\n\n\n    This dual extraction and injection mechanism is designed to enrich the global\nconditioning available to the decoder by combining invariant representations ex-\ntracted at different hierarchical levels. The frame-level RVQ stream remains\nunchanged, while the additional TIRE branch introduces a second global condi-\ntioning signal.\n\n\n3     Protocol and Probing Tasks\nTo analyze the information actually captured by the TIRE representations, we\nadopt a diagnostic probing approach that consists of evaluating their capacity\n\f6       K. Estève et al.\n\nto encode the information necessary for a set of targeted classification tasks.\nThe underlying premise is that strong performance on a given task indicates the\npresence of the relevant information, while weak performance suggests that the\ninformation is absent or significantly attenuated.\n    To evaluate the intrinsic quality of the extracted features, the representations\nproduced by the TIRE module are kept frozen and used as inputs to a down-\nstream diagnostic classifier. This classifier is a Multi-Layer Perceptron (MLP)\ncomposed of two fully-connected hidden layers of 1,024 neurons each, followed\nby an output layer adapted to the task. All experiments are evaluated using\naccuracy. By keeping the codec frozen and avoiding joint fine-tuning, this pro-\ntocol ensures that we explicitly measure the information already captured and\npreserved by the TIRE representations.\n    To cover a wide range of information likely to be encoded in TIRE represen-\ntations, we consider five representative classification tasks, ranging from speaker\nidentity to linguistic and semantic content.\nSpeaker Identification: This task aims to determine whether an acoustic rep-\nresentation contains sufficient discriminative information to identify a speaker\nby their voice. In this framework, the problem is formulated as a multi-class\nclassification, where each class corresponds to a distinct speaker. TIRE repre-\nsentations are used to train a classifier on 1,022 speakers from the VoxCeleb1\ndataset [10].\nAcoustic Scene Classification: This task evaluates the capacity of TIRE rep-\nresentations to capture information related to the acoustic environment. We use\nthe TAU Urban Acoustic Scenes corpus [11], composed of 10 classes correspond-\ning to different urban sound contexts (Airport, Bus, Metro, Park, etc.).\nEmotion Recognition: Emotion recognition aims to analyze whether represen-\ntations derived from TiCodec preserve paralinguistic parameters, such as intona-\ntion, energy, or speech rhythm. This task is performed on the MELD corpus [12],\nwhich provides annotations for 7 emotional classes.\nSpoken Language Identification: This task measures the capacity of repre-\nsentations to encode high-level linguistic information, particularly the phonetic\nand prosodic characteristics specific to a language. We use a multilingual ver-\nsion of the Common Voice corpus [13], covering 45 languages. High accuracy\nin this task would indicate that TIRE representations retain sufficient param-\neters to differentiate languages, despite the compression process performed by\nthe neural codec.\nKeyword Spotting: Finally, the keyword spotting task aims to evaluate the\npreservation of local lexical information. We use the Google Speech Commands\ncorpus [14], composed of 35 classes corresponding to different keywords (Yes,\nNo, Up, Down, Left, Right, etc.).\n\n\n4   Experiments and Results\n\nThis section presents the experimental setup and results. It introduces the datasets\nand evaluation metrics (Section 4.1), then analyzes the standard TiCodec archi-\n\f   Streaming Neural Speech Codecs through Time-Invariant Representations            7\n\ntecture: the impact of the TIRE connection layer together with a probing char-\nacterization of the encoded information (Section 4.2), and the segment selection\nstrategies used during TIRE training (Section 4.3). Building on these analyses,\nwe finally evaluate the proposed Dual-TIRE architecture (Section 4.4).\n\n\n4.1   Experimental Protocol\n\nWe first describe the speech corpora used for training and evaluation, followed\nby the objective metrics adopted to assess speech quality, intelligibility, spectral\nfidelity, and speaker identity preservation.\nTraining: The TiCodec model is trained on the LibriTTS corpus [15], a multi-\nspeaker English read speech dataset recorded at a sampling rate of 24 kHz. Lib-\nriTTS is derived from the materials used to create LibriSpeech [16], combining\naudio recordings from LibriVox and text transcriptions from Project Gutenberg.\nThe corpus totals approximately 585 hours of speech, produced by 2,456 speak-\ners. For training, we use the train-clean-100, train-clean-360, and train-other-500\nsubsets.\nEvaluation: The evaluation of the different models is performed on the Lib-\nriTTS test-clean [15], VCTK [17] and EMILIA [18]. For EMILIA, 4,000 utter-\nances are randomly selected for each language: French, German, Japanese and\nKorean.\nMetrics: Speech quality and intelligibility assessment was performed using the\nfollowing metrics: ViSQOL V3 (Virtual Speech Quality Objective Listener) [19],\nPESQ (Perceptual Evaluation of Speech Quality) [20], STOI (Short-Time Ob-\njective Intelligibility) [21], and Mel Cepstral Distortion (MCD) [22]. Speaker\nidentity preservation is evaluated using Sim, computed as the cosine similarity\nbetween speaker embeddings extracted from the original and reconstructed ut-\nterances using a pretrained speaker-verification model. Higher values indicate\nbetter preservation of speaker identity. All these metrics allow for a joint evalu-\nation of global perceptual quality, intelligibility, spectral fidelity, as well as the\npreservation of speaker characteristics. Together, they provide a comprehensive\nassessment of system performance.\n\n\n4.2   Analysis of the Impact of the TIRE Module Connection Layer\n\nTo investigate the informative potential of other layers within the architecture,\nwe trained several distinct systems in which the TIRE module is connected to\nlayers 1, 2, 3, and 4, respectively, in a symmetric manner across the encoder and\ndecoder. The objective of this study is to identify the layer yielding the richest\nrepresentations while limiting redundancy with time-dependent information.\n    Table 1 reports the results, on the LibriTTS test-clean corpus, obtained for\na reference system without the TIRE module (No-TIRE ), as well as for the\ndifferent variants where TIRE is connected to the corresponding encoder and\ndecoder layers.\n\f8       K. Estève et al.\n\nTable 1. Impact of the TIRE injection layer on LibriTTS test-clean. Intermediate\nlayers (2 and 3) provide the best trade-off between perceptual quality, intelligibility,\nspectral fidelity, and speaker similarity. Best results are shown in bold.\n\n         TIRE injection layer ViSQOL↑ PESQ↑ STOI↑ MCD↓ Sim↑\n         No-TIRE (baseline)          4.362     2.797    0.938    0.772   0.703\n         Layer 1                     4.373     2.897    0.942 0.742 0.721\n         Layer 2                     4.382     2.956    0.944 0.728 0.699\n         Layer 3                     4.406     2.876    0.942 0.762 0.722\n         Layer 4                     4.328     2.748    0.935 0.794 0.696\n\n\n\n\n   Analysis of Table 1 indicates that TIRE generally improves metrics over the\nNo-TIRE baseline, except for Layer 4. However, improvements are not uniform\nacross all criteria, as speaker similarity does not always increase. Among the\nvarious configurations, the systems utilizing Layers 2 and 3 appear to offer the\nbest trade-off. Specifically, the system using Layer 2 optimizes signal sharpness\nand fine structure, achieving a PESQ score of 2.956 and an MCD of 0.728. Con-\nversely, the system trained on Layer 3 favors superior global perceptual fidelity\nand better preservation of speaker identity, as evidenced by a ViSQOL score of\n4.406 and a Sim score of 0.722.\n   To better understand the nature of the information driving these perfor-\nmance differences, we evaluated the frozen TIRE representations from each en-\ncoder layer across the five selected downstream probing classification tasks (see\nSection 3).\n\n\n\n\nFig. 3. Probing evaluation of TIRE representations extracted from encoder Layers 1–4\nacross five downstream classification tasks, highlighting the types of information cap-\ntured at each layer and the progressive loss of informative content in deeper compressed\nrepresentations.\n\f   Streaming Neural Speech Codecs through Time-Invariant Representations         9\n\n    The results presented in Figure 3 indicate that Layers 1, 2, and 3 generally\ncapture information of a similar nature. We observe that the TIRE module\nencodes parameters related to acoustic scenes and emotions, suggesting effective\ncapture of global and paralinguistic signal attributes. Conversely, performance\non spoken language identification and keyword spotting tasks is near chance\nlevel, indicating that the TIRE module does not retain fine-grained linguistic or\nlexical information.\n    Regarding speaker identity, the results remain moderate. Although some dis-\ncriminative information is present, the relatively low performance suggests that\nthe TIRE module does not explicitly encode speaker identity, but rather high-\nlevel acoustic features likely correlated with it.\n    Finally, a marked degradation in performance is observed for Layer 4, re-\ngardless of the task considered. This layer does not appear to encode information\nexploitable by the TIRE module, likely because the resulting representations are\ntoo compressed.\n\n\n4.3   Analysis of Segment Selection Strategies for TIRE Module\n      Training\n\nDuring the training of TiCodec, and specifically the TIRE module, two audio\nsegments are extracted from the audio file to constrain the learning of invariant\nrepresentations. In the standard configuration, these two segments are drawn\nrandomly from the same audio file, without any explicit constraint on their\ntemporal positions.\n    The underlying principle is to encourage TIRE to produce similar representa-\ntions for segments sharing common global attributes (speaker identity, acoustic\nscene), while reducing the influence of time-dependent information, such as pho-\nnetic or lexical content. In other words, the TIRE module is incentivized to\nminimize representation variations between two segments originating from the\nsame source, regardless of their local differences, in order to foster the encoding\nof invariant information.\n    However, the manner in which these segments are selected during training\ncan have a direct impact on the nature of the information effectively learned.\nIn this section, we propose five distinct segment selection strategies. Each strat-\negy defines a specific sampling policy for the two segments used during TIRE\ntraining:\n\n – Random segments (unconstrained): Two segments are extracted ran-\n   domly from the same audio file, without any constraints on their temporal\n   positions. The segments may overlap. This strategy corresponds to the de-\n   fault configuration and serves as a baseline.\n – Random non-overlapping segments: Two segments are extracted ran-\n   domly from the same file, with the additional constraint that they do not\n   overlap in time. This strategy aims to reduce direct redundancy between\n   segments while retaining an identical global context.\n\f10      K. Estève et al.\n\n – Adjacent segments: The first segment is extracted randomly from the file,\n   and the second segment corresponds to the contiguous segment immediately\n   following the first. This strategy introduces strong temporal correlation be-\n   tween segments and favors local signal continuity.\n – Cross-file (same speaker): The first segment is extracted from the cur-\n   rent file, while the second is extracted from a different file belonging to the\n   same speaker. By exploiting recordings from different sessions of the same\n   speaker, this strategy allows TIRE to build a representation space that better\n   accounts for speaker variability (e.g., changes in channel, recording condi-\n   tions, or speaking style).\n – Cross-file (same speaker and book): The first segment is extracted from\n   the current file, and the second from a different file recorded by the same\n   speaker and originating from the same book. This strategy reduces speaker\n   variability.\n\n   The results presented in Table 2 show that the segment extraction strat-\negy influences performance differently depending on the Layer 2 and 3. When\nrepresentations are extracted at Layer 2, the unconstrained strategy (random\nsegments) offers the best performance across all metrics, suggesting that free\nextraction favors a good trade-off between reconstruction quality and speaker\nidentity preservation.\n\n\nTable 2. Impact of segment selection strategies during TIRE training on LibriTTS\ntest-clean. Representations are extracted from encoder Layer 2 and Layer 3. Best results\nwithin each Layer are shown in bold.\n\n Segment selection strategy / Layer ViSQOL↑ PESQ↑ STOI↑ MCD↓ Sim↑\n                                        Layer 2\n Random segments (unconstrained)             4.382      2.956   0.944 0.728 0.699\n Random non-overlapping segments             4.355      2.827   0.940 0.763 0.691\n Adjacent segments                           4.373      2.901   0.944 0.744 0.696\n Cross-file (same speaker)                   4.363      2.859   0.942 0.749 0.687", "numLines": 300, "startLine": 250, "totalLines": 804}}}
