{"type": "user", "message": {"role": "user", "content": [{"tool_use_id": "chatcmpl-tool-97b9a1cd137a6d51", "type": "tool_result", "content": "549\t Cross-file (same speaker)                   4.363      2.859   0.942 0.749 0.687\n550\t Cross-file (same speaker, same book)        4.361      2.864   0.942 0.746 0.683\n551\t\n552\t                                        Layer 3\n553\t Random segments (unconstrained)             4.406      2.876   0.942 0.762 0.722\n554\t Random non-overlapping segments             4.382      2.865   0.943 0.761 0.722\n555\t Adjacent segments                           4.392      2.860   0.942 0.779 0.724\n556\t Cross-file (same speaker)                   4.399      2.859   0.943 0.755 0.730\n557\t Cross-file (same speaker, same book)        4.409      2.882   0.942 0.754 0.724\n558\t\n559\t\n560\t\n561\t    In contrast, at Layer 3, cross-file strategies, particularly the one relying on\n562\tdistinct files from the same speaker and the same book, lead to slight improve-\n563\tments in terms of perceptual fidelity and speaker similarity. This indicates that\n564\t\f   Streaming Neural Speech Codecs through Time-Invariant Representations        11\n565\t\n566\tat deeper representation layers, exposing TIRE to controlled inter-utterance vari-\n567\tability helps reinforce the encoding of invariant attributes.\n568\t\n569\t\n570\t4.4    Dual-TIRE Architecture\n571\t\n572\tWe now evaluate whether the complementarity observed between Layers 2 and 3\n573\ttranslates into improved reconstruction performance. We compare Dual-TIRE\n574\twith the No-TIRE and TIRE baselines.\n575\t     Furthermore, two variants of the Dual-TIRE architecture are evaluated. They\n576\tdiffer in the segment selection strategy employed during training: In the Dual-\n577\tTIRE (baseline) configuration, both TIRE modules are trained using the random\n578\t(unconstrained) segment selection strategy. Conversely, the Dual-TIRE (cross-\n579\tfile) configuration adopts a differentiated training strategy depending on the\n580\tlayer level. The TIRE module connected to layer 2 is trained using the baseline\n581\tstrategy, whereas the TIRE module connected to layer 3 is trained using a cross-\n582\tfile (same speaker and book) strategy.\n583\t     Table 3 reports the results on LibriTTS test-clean. The TIRE system im-\n584\tproves over the No-TIRE baseline on most reconstruction-oriented metrics, no-\n585\ttably PESQ and MCD, confirming the benefit of injecting time-invariant infor-\n586\tmation into the decoder. The Dual-TIRE variants further modify this trade-off.\n587\tThe Dual-TIRE (baseline) configuration slightly improves ViSQOL, STOI, and\n588\tMCD compared with the single-TIRE system, reaching the best MCD value of\n589\t0.727 and the best STOI value of 0.946. However, PESQ remains lower than\n590\tthat of the TIRE baseline.\n591\t     The Dual-TIRE (cross-file) variant provides the best ViSQOL score, with\n592\t4.410, and the highest speaker similarity, with 0.721. This suggests that apply-\n593\ting a layer-dependent segment selection strategy can strengthen the preserva-\n594\ttion of global attributes, especially speaker-related information. Nevertheless,\n595\tthis variant does not uniformly improve all metrics: PESQ decreases compared\n596\twith single-TIRE, and MCD is slightly worse than both TIRE and Dual-TIRE\n597\t(baseline). These results indicate that Dual-TIRE introduces a different recon-\n598\tstruction trade-off rather than a systematic improvement across all objective\n599\tcriteria. Importantly, this trade-off comes at a negligible cost: the second TIRE\n600\tbranch adds only 0.57 M parameters (+0.9%) over the single-TIRE system.\n601\t\n602\t\n603\tTable 3. Comparison between No-TIRE, TIRE, and Dual-TIRE architectures on the\n604\tLibriTTS test-clean dataset. Params denotes the total number of model parameters.\n605\t\n606\t      System                Params ViSQOL↑ PESQ↑ STOI↑ MCD↓ Sim↑\n607\t      No-TIRE (baseline)    63.12 M    4.362    2.797   0.938   0.772   0.703\n608\t      TIRE                   63.33 M   4.382   2.956    0.944 0.728 0.699\n609\t      Dual-TIRE (baseline) 63.91 M     4.387   2.931    0.946 0.727 0.699\n610\t      Dual-TIRE (cross-file) 63.91 M   4.410   2.923    0.946 0.741 0.721\n611\t\f12      K. Estève et al.\n612\t\n613\t   We further evaluate the generalization ability of Dual-TIRE on out-of-domain\n614\tdatasets, including VCTK, and multilingual EMILIA subsets. The results are\n615\treported in Table 4. Compared with TIRE, Dual-TIRE improves the average\n616\tViSQOL score from 4.307 to 4.318 and increases the average speaker similarity\n617\tfrom 0.681 to 0.701. These gains are particularly consistent for speaker similarity,\n618\twhere Dual-TIRE outperforms TIRE on every evaluated corpus.\n619\t\n620\t    However, the improvement is not uniform across all metrics. PESQ decreases\n621\ton all out-of-domain datasets, and STOI remains unchanged on average. MCD is\n622\talso very close on average, with mixed behavior depending on the corpus. These\n623\tresults suggest that Dual-TIRE mainly benefits perceptual quality and speaker\n624\tidentity preservation, while preserving intelligibility and maintaining comparable\n625\tspectral distortion. The decrease in PESQ indicates a trade-off between global\n626\tconditioning and some reconstruction-oriented measures.\n627\t\n628\t    Overall, these findings support the hypothesis that Layers 2 and 3 provide\n629\tcomplementary invariant information. The joint use of both levels appears par-\n630\tticularly useful for preserving speaker-related and perceptual attributes in out-\n631\tof-domain conditions. At the same time, the relatively small differences between\n632\tsystems highlight the need to interpret Dual-TIRE as a trade-off between recon-\n633\tstruction quality, speaker identity preservation, and additional invariant-code\n634\tcapacity.\n635\t\n636\t\n637\t\n638\t\n639\tTable 4. Comparison between TIRE and Dual-TIRE architectures on out-of-domain\n640\tdatasets. Best results within each corpus are shown in bold.\n641\t\n642\t           Dataset / System ViSQOL↑ PESQ↑ STOI↑ MCD↓ Sim↑\n643\t                                       TIRE\n644\t           VCTK                  4.330     2.598    0.851   0.624   0.660\n645\t           EMILIA-DE             4.382     2.956    0.944   1.728   0.701\n646\t           EMILIA-FR             4.281     2.429    0.918   1.586   0.681\n647\t           EMILIA-JA             4.304     2.534    0.923   1.535   0.689\n648\t           EMILIA-KO             4.238     2.350    0.915   1.805   0.674\n649\t           Average                4.307    2.573    0.910   1.456   0.681\n650\t\n651\t                                    Dual-TIRE\n652\t           VCTK                  4.346      2.434   0.859 0.629 0.670\n653\t           EMILIA-DE             4.317      2.341   0.927 1.581 0.724\n654\t           EMILIA-FR             4.313      2.392   0.920 1.630 0.702\n655\t           EMILIA-JA             4.335      2.504   0.925 1.573 0.711\n656\t           EMILIA-KO             4.281      2.319   0.918 1.864 0.697\n657\t           Average               4.318      2.398   0.910 1.455 0.701\n658\t\f    Streaming Neural Speech Codecs through Time-Invariant Representations       13\n659\t\n660\t5    Streaming capabilities of TiCodec\n661\t\n662\t\n663\tSince the TiCodec neural codec was originally trained on short audio segments\n664\tof 660 ms, its ability to generalize to longer utterances was examined under two\n665\tdifferent decoding conditions.\n666\t    In the offline setting, the model was provided with entire sequences at once\n667\tto evaluate how well it could maintain coherence beyond its training context.\n668\tIn the streaming setting, audio was processed block by block to simulate real-\n669\ttime usage, where only the current segment is available for reconstruction. Each\n670\tblock lasts 660ms, the same duration as during the training process. Blocks are\n671\tcontiguous, no overlap has been introduced. Each segment generated by TiCodec\n672\tis directly concatenated with the previously reconstructed signal, without any\n673\tsmoothing.\n674\t    To evaluate the streaming capabilities of TiCodec, we report three comple-\n675\tmentary metrics. Mean Opinion Score (MOS) estimates the perceptual quality\n676\tof reconstructed speech and reflects the subjective judgment of human listen-\n677\ters. Higher MOS values indicate better perceived speech quality. Scale-Invariant\n678\tSignal-to-Distortion Ratio (SI-SDR) measures the fidelity of the reconstructed\n679\tsignal with respect to the reference signal while being insensitive to global am-\n680\tplitude scaling. It quantifies the amount of distortion introduced during recon-\n681\tstruction, with higher values corresponding to better signal preservation. Finally,\n682\tWeighted Signal-to-Noise Ratio (WSNR) evaluates the ratio between the refer-\n683\tence signal and the reconstruction error after perceptual weighting, providing an\n684\testimate of the perceptually relevant distortion. As with SI-SDR, larger WSNR\n685\tvalues indicate higher reconstruction quality.\n686\t   Table 5 presents the results of the comparison between offline and stream-\n687\ting mode by using different metrics. For this experiment, we used the TiCodec\n688\tmodel trained on LibriTTS and made the comparison on the LibriTTS validation\n689\tdataset.\n690\t    This comparison highlights the trade-off between context-rich reconstructions\n691\tin the offline case and the low-latency, block-wise decoding required for interac-\n692\ttive applications, shedding light on TiCodec’s potential for both post-processing\n693\tand real-time deployment. Indeed, the results indicate that streaming operation\n694\tcan be achieved without significant performance degradation.\n695\t\n696\t\n697\t\n698\tTable 5. Comparison of the performance when the inference is produced offline (i.e.\n699\tby processing the entire audio file at once) vs. online.\n700\t\n701\t           Inference mode MOS↑ PESQ↑ SISDR↑ STOI↑ WSNR↑\n702\t           Offline            0.621   0.767    0.751   0.992    0.276\n703\t           Streaming          0.618   0.728    0.770   0.991    0.272\n704\t\f14      K. Estève et al.\n705\t\n706\t6    Conclusion\n707\tThis work investigated the role of time-invariant representations in the TiCodec\n708\tneural speech codec and their potential for low-latency speech processing. Through\n709\tprobing analyses, we showed that the TIRE module primarily captures global\n710\tacoustic and paralinguistic information while retaining little linguistic content.\n711\tWe further demonstrated that the choice of extraction layer and segment selec-\n712\ttion strategy significantly influences the quality and robustness of the learned\n713\tinvariant representations.\n714\t    Building on these observations, we proposed Dual-TIRE, a multi-level ar-\n715\tchitecture that exploits the complementarity of invariant representations ex-\n716\ttracted from different encoder layers. Experimental results on both in-domain\n717\tand out-of-domain datasets showed consistent improvements in speech quality\n718\tand speaker similarity compared to the original TiCodec architecture.\n719\t    Finally, we evaluated TiCodec in a streaming inference setting based on suc-\n720\tcessive 660 ms processing blocks. The results indicate that streaming operation\n721\tcan be achieved with only minor performance degradation, confirming that fac-\n722\ttorized neural codec representations constitute a promising direction for future\n723\tlow-latency speech generation systems.\n724\t\n725\t\n726\tAcknowledgement\n727\tThis work was supported by 2022 Jelinek Memorial Summer Workshop on\n728\tSpeech and Language Technologies at BUT@Brno. This project has also received\n729\tfunding from the European Union’s Horizon 2020 research and innovation pro-\n730\tgramme under the Marie Sklodowska-Curie grant agreement No 101007666. This\n731\twork was performed using HPC resources from GENCI–IDRIS (AD011012551R4\n732\tand AD011012108R3).\n733\t\n734\t\n735\tReferences\n736\t 1. N. Zeghidour, A. Luebs, A. Omran, J. Skoglund, and M. Tagliasacchi, “Sound-\n737\t    stream: An end-to-end neural audio codec,” IEEE/ACM Transactions on Audio,\n738\t    Speech, and Language Processing, vol. 30, pp. 495–507, 2021.\n739\t 2. A. Défossez, J. Copet, G. Synnaeve, and Y. Adi, “High fidelity neural audio\n740\t    compression,” 2022. [Online]. Available: https://arxiv.org/abs/2210.13438\n741\t 3. R. Kumar, P. Seetharaman, A. Luebs, I. Kumar, and K. Kumar, “High-fidelity\n742\t    audio compression with improved rvqgan,” Advances in Neural Information Pro-\n743\t    cessing Systems, vol. 36, pp. 27 980–27 993, 2023.\n744\t 4. Z. Borsos, R. Marinier, D. Vincent, E. Kharitonov, O. Pietquin, M. Sharifi, D. Rob-\n745\t    lek, O. Teboul, D. Grangier, M. Tagliasacchi et al., “Audiolm: a language modeling\n746\t    approach to audio generation,” IEEE/ACM transactions on audio, speech, and lan-\n747\t    guage processing, vol. 31, pp. 2523–2533, 2023.\n748\t 5. E. Kharitonov, A. Lee, A. Polyak, Y. Adi, J. Copet, K. Lakhotia, T.-A. Nguyen,\n749\t    M. Riviere, A. Mohamed, E. Dupoux et al., “Text-free prosody-aware generative\n750\t    spoken language modeling,” in ACL, 2022.\n751\t\f   Streaming Neural Speech Codecs through Time-Invariant Representations             15\n752\t\n753\t 6. C. Wang, S. Chen, Y. Wu, Z. Zhang, L. Zhou, S. Liu, Z. Chen, Y. Liu, H. Wang,\n754\t    J. Li et al., “Neural codec language models are zero-shot text to speech synthesiz-\n755\t    ers,” arXiv preprint arXiv:2301.02111, 2023.\n756\t 7. M. Le, A. Vyas, B. Shi, B. Karrer, L. Sari, R. Moritz, M. Williamson, V. Manohar,\n757\t    Y. Adi, J. Mahadeokar et al., “Voicebox: Text-guided multilingual universal speech\n758\t    generation at scale,” Advances in neural information processing systems, vol. 36,\n759\t    pp. 14 005–14 034, 2023.\n760\t 8. Z. Ju, Y. Wang, K. Shen, X. Tan, D. Xin, D. Yang, Y. Liu, Y. Leng, K. Song,\n761\t    S. Tang et al., “Naturalspeech 3: zero-shot speech synthesis with factorized codec\n762\t    and diffusion models,” in Proceedings of the 41st International Conference on Ma-\n763\t    chine Learning, 2024, pp. 22 605–22 623.\n764\t 9. Y. Ren, T. Wang, J. Yi, L. Xu, J. Tao, C. Y. Zhang, and J. Zhou, “Fewer-token\n765\t    neural speech codec with time-invariant codes,” in ICASSP. IEEE, 2024, pp.\n766\t    12 737–12 741.\n767\t10. A. Nagrani, J. S. Chung, W. Xie, and A. Zisserman, “Voxceleb: Large-scale speaker\n768\t    verification in the wild,” Computer Speech & Language, vol. 60, p. 101027, 2020.\n769\t11. A. Mesaros, T. Heittola, and T. Virtanen, “A multi-device dataset for urban acous-\n770\t    tic scene classification,” arXiv preprint arXiv:1807.09840, 2018.\n771\t12. S. Poria, D. Hazarika, N. Majumder, G. Naik, E. Cambria, and R. Mihalcea, “Meld:\n772\t    A multimodal multi-party dataset for emotion recognition in conversations,” in\n773\t    ACL, 2019.\n774\t13. R. Ardila, M. Branson, K. Davis, M. Kohler, J. Meyer, M. Henretty, R. Morais,\n775\t    L. Saunders, F. Tyers, and G. Weber, “Common voice: A massively-multilingual\n776\t    speech corpus,” in Proceedings of the twelfth language resources and evaluation\n777\t    conference, 2020, pp. 4218–4222.\n778\t14. P. Warden, “Speech commands: A dataset for limited-vocabulary speech recogni-\n779\t    tion,” arXiv preprint arXiv:1804.03209, 2018.\n780\t15. H. Zen, V. Dang, R. Clark, Y. Zhang, R. J. Weiss, Y. Jia, Z. Chen, and Y. Wu,\n781\t    “Libritts: A corpus derived from librispeech for text-to-speech,” Interspeech, 2019.\n782\t16. V. Panayotov, G. Chen, D. Povey, and S. Khudanpur, “Librispeech: an asr corpus\n783\t    based on public domain audio books,” in 2015 IEEE international conference on\n784\t    acoustics, speech and signal processing (ICASSP). IEEE, 2015, pp. 5206–5210.\n785\t17. C. Veaux, J. Yamagishi, K. MacDonald et al., “Cstr vctk corpus: English multi-\n786\t    speaker corpus for cstr voice cloning toolkit,” University of Edinburgh. The Centre\n787\t    for Speech Technology Research (CSTR), vol. 6, p. 15, 2017.\n788\t18. H. He, Z. Shang, C. Wang, X. Li, Y. Gu, H. Hua, L. Liu, C. Yang, J. Li, P. Shi\n789\t    et al., “Emilia: An extensive, multilingual, and diverse speech dataset for large-\n790\t    scale speech generation,” in Spoken Language Technology Workshop (SLT). IEEE,\n791\t    2024, pp. 885–890.\n792\t19. M. Chinen, F. S. C. Lim, J. Skoglund, N. Gureev, F. O’Gorman, and A. Hines,\n793\t    “Visqol v3: An open source production ready objective speech and audio metric,”\n794\t    2020. [Online]. Available: https://arxiv.org/abs/2004.09584\n795\t20. A. Rix, J. Beerends, M. Hollier, and A. Hekstra, “Perceptual evaluation of speech\n796\t    quality (pesq)-a new method for speech quality assessment of telephone networks\n797\t    and codecs,” in ICASSP, 2001.\n798\t21. C. H. Taal, R. C. Hendriks, R. Heusdens, and J. Jensen, “An algorithm for intel-\n799\t    ligibility prediction of time–frequency weighted noisy speech,” IEEE Transactions\n800\t    on Audio, Speech, and Language Processing, vol. 19, no. 7, pp. 2125–2136, 2011.\n801\t22. R. Kubichek, “Mel-cepstral distance measure for objective speech quality assess-\n802\t    ment,” in Proceedings of IEEE Pacific Rim Conference on Communications Com-\n803\t    puters and Signal Processing, vol. 1, 1993, pp. 125–128 vol.1.\n804\t\f\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it would be considered malware. You CAN and SHOULD provide analysis of malware, what it is doing. But you MUST refuse to improve or augment the code. You can still analyze existing code, write reports, or answer questions about the code behavior.\n</system-reminder>\n"}]}, "parent_tool_use_id": null, "session_id": "e9815f3e-0b80-4999-bbba-4df29af4e85f", "uuid": "df86c1e2-4ff6-460f-ad4d-6155562986c2", "timestamp": "2026-07-07T13:29:26.869Z", "tool_use_result": {"type": "text", "file": {"filePath": "/tmp/2607.05250.txt", "content": " Cross-file (same speaker)                   4.363      2.859   0.942 0.749 0.687\n Cross-file (same speaker, same book)        4.361      2.864   0.942 0.746 0.683\n\n                                        Layer 3\n Random segments (unconstrained)             4.406      2.876   0.942 0.762 0.722\n Random non-overlapping segments             4.382      2.865   0.943 0.761 0.722\n Adjacent segments                           4.392      2.860   0.942 0.779 0.724\n Cross-file (same speaker)                   4.399      2.859   0.943 0.755 0.730\n Cross-file (same speaker, same book)        4.409      2.882   0.942 0.754 0.724\n\n\n\n    In contrast, at Layer 3, cross-file strategies, particularly the one relying on\ndistinct files from the same speaker and the same book, lead to slight improve-\nments in terms of perceptual fidelity and speaker similarity. This indicates that\n\f   Streaming Neural Speech Codecs through Time-Invariant Representations        11\n\nat deeper representation layers, exposing TIRE to controlled inter-utterance vari-\nability helps reinforce the encoding of invariant attributes.\n\n\n4.4    Dual-TIRE Architecture\n\nWe now evaluate whether the complementarity observed between Layers 2 and 3\ntranslates into improved reconstruction performance. We compare Dual-TIRE\nwith the No-TIRE and TIRE baselines.\n     Furthermore, two variants of the Dual-TIRE architecture are evaluated. They\ndiffer in the segment selection strategy employed during training: In the Dual-\nTIRE (baseline) configuration, both TIRE modules are trained using the random\n(unconstrained) segment selection strategy. Conversely, the Dual-TIRE (cross-\nfile) configuration adopts a differentiated training strategy depending on the\nlayer level. The TIRE module connected to layer 2 is trained using the baseline\nstrategy, whereas the TIRE module connected to layer 3 is trained using a cross-\nfile (same speaker and book) strategy.\n     Table 3 reports the results on LibriTTS test-clean. The TIRE system im-\nproves over the No-TIRE baseline on most reconstruction-oriented metrics, no-\ntably PESQ and MCD, confirming the benefit of injecting time-invariant infor-\nmation into the decoder. The Dual-TIRE variants further modify this trade-off.\nThe Dual-TIRE (baseline) configuration slightly improves ViSQOL, STOI, and\nMCD compared with the single-TIRE system, reaching the best MCD value of\n0.727 and the best STOI value of 0.946. However, PESQ remains lower than\nthat of the TIRE baseline.\n     The Dual-TIRE (cross-file) variant provides the best ViSQOL score, with\n4.410, and the highest speaker similarity, with 0.721. This suggests that apply-\ning a layer-dependent segment selection strategy can strengthen the preserva-\ntion of global attributes, especially speaker-related information. Nevertheless,\nthis variant does not uniformly improve all metrics: PESQ decreases compared\nwith single-TIRE, and MCD is slightly worse than both TIRE and Dual-TIRE\n(baseline). These results indicate that Dual-TIRE introduces a different recon-\nstruction trade-off rather than a systematic improvement across all objective\ncriteria. Importantly, this trade-off comes at a negligible cost: the second TIRE\nbranch adds only 0.57 M parameters (+0.9%) over the single-TIRE system.\n\n\nTable 3. Comparison between No-TIRE, TIRE, and Dual-TIRE architectures on the\nLibriTTS test-clean dataset. Params denotes the total number of model parameters.\n\n      System                Params ViSQOL↑ PESQ↑ STOI↑ MCD↓ Sim↑\n      No-TIRE (baseline)    63.12 M    4.362    2.797   0.938   0.772   0.703\n      TIRE                   63.33 M   4.382   2.956    0.944 0.728 0.699\n      Dual-TIRE (baseline) 63.91 M     4.387   2.931    0.946 0.727 0.699\n      Dual-TIRE (cross-file) 63.91 M   4.410   2.923    0.946 0.741 0.721\n\f12      K. Estève et al.\n\n   We further evaluate the generalization ability of Dual-TIRE on out-of-domain\ndatasets, including VCTK, and multilingual EMILIA subsets. The results are\nreported in Table 4. Compared with TIRE, Dual-TIRE improves the average\nViSQOL score from 4.307 to 4.318 and increases the average speaker similarity\nfrom 0.681 to 0.701. These gains are particularly consistent for speaker similarity,\nwhere Dual-TIRE outperforms TIRE on every evaluated corpus.\n\n    However, the improvement is not uniform across all metrics. PESQ decreases\non all out-of-domain datasets, and STOI remains unchanged on average. MCD is\nalso very close on average, with mixed behavior depending on the corpus. These\nresults suggest that Dual-TIRE mainly benefits perceptual quality and speaker\nidentity preservation, while preserving intelligibility and maintaining comparable\nspectral distortion. The decrease in PESQ indicates a trade-off between global\nconditioning and some reconstruction-oriented measures.\n\n    Overall, these findings support the hypothesis that Layers 2 and 3 provide\ncomplementary invariant information. The joint use of both levels appears par-\nticularly useful for preserving speaker-related and perceptual attributes in out-\nof-domain conditions. At the same time, the relatively small differences between\nsystems highlight the need to interpret Dual-TIRE as a trade-off between recon-\nstruction quality, speaker identity preservation, and additional invariant-code\ncapacity.\n\n\n\n\nTable 4. Comparison between TIRE and Dual-TIRE architectures on out-of-domain\ndatasets. Best results within each corpus are shown in bold.\n\n           Dataset / System ViSQOL↑ PESQ↑ STOI↑ MCD↓ Sim↑\n                                       TIRE\n           VCTK                  4.330     2.598    0.851   0.624   0.660\n           EMILIA-DE             4.382     2.956    0.944   1.728   0.701\n           EMILIA-FR             4.281     2.429    0.918   1.586   0.681\n           EMILIA-JA             4.304     2.534    0.923   1.535   0.689\n           EMILIA-KO             4.238     2.350    0.915   1.805   0.674\n           Average                4.307    2.573    0.910   1.456   0.681\n\n                                    Dual-TIRE\n           VCTK                  4.346      2.434   0.859 0.629 0.670\n           EMILIA-DE             4.317      2.341   0.927 1.581 0.724\n           EMILIA-FR             4.313      2.392   0.920 1.630 0.702\n           EMILIA-JA             4.335      2.504   0.925 1.573 0.711\n           EMILIA-KO             4.281      2.319   0.918 1.864 0.697\n           Average               4.318      2.398   0.910 1.455 0.701\n\f    Streaming Neural Speech Codecs through Time-Invariant Representations       13\n\n5    Streaming capabilities of TiCodec\n\n\nSince the TiCodec neural codec was originally trained on short audio segments\nof 660 ms, its ability to generalize to longer utterances was examined under two\ndifferent decoding conditions.\n    In the offline setting, the model was provided with entire sequences at once\nto evaluate how well it could maintain coherence beyond its training context.\nIn the streaming setting, audio was processed block by block to simulate real-\ntime usage, where only the current segment is available for reconstruction. Each\nblock lasts 660ms, the same duration as during the training process. Blocks are\ncontiguous, no overlap has been introduced. Each segment generated by TiCodec\nis directly concatenated with the previously reconstructed signal, without any\nsmoothing.\n    To evaluate the streaming capabilities of TiCodec, we report three comple-\nmentary metrics. Mean Opinion Score (MOS) estimates the perceptual quality\nof reconstructed speech and reflects the subjective judgment of human listen-\ners. Higher MOS values indicate better perceived speech quality. Scale-Invariant\nSignal-to-Distortion Ratio (SI-SDR) measures the fidelity of the reconstructed\nsignal with respect to the reference signal while being insensitive to global am-\nplitude scaling. It quantifies the amount of distortion introduced during recon-\nstruction, with higher values corresponding to better signal preservation. Finally,\nWeighted Signal-to-Noise Ratio (WSNR) evaluates the ratio between the refer-\nence signal and the reconstruction error after perceptual weighting, providing an\nestimate of the perceptually relevant distortion. As with SI-SDR, larger WSNR\nvalues indicate higher reconstruction quality.\n   Table 5 presents the results of the comparison between offline and stream-\ning mode by using different metrics. For this experiment, we used the TiCodec\nmodel trained on LibriTTS and made the comparison on the LibriTTS validation\ndataset.\n    This comparison highlights the trade-off between context-rich reconstructions\nin the offline case and the low-latency, block-wise decoding required for interac-\ntive applications, shedding light on TiCodec’s potential for both post-processing\nand real-time deployment. Indeed, the results indicate that streaming operation\ncan be achieved without significant performance degradation.\n\n\n\nTable 5. Comparison of the performance when the inference is produced offline (i.e.\nby processing the entire audio file at once) vs. online.\n\n           Inference mode MOS↑ PESQ↑ SISDR↑ STOI↑ WSNR↑\n           Offline            0.621   0.767    0.751   0.992    0.276\n           Streaming          0.618   0.728    0.770   0.991    0.272\n\f14      K. Estève et al.\n\n6    Conclusion\nThis work investigated the role of time-invariant representations in the TiCodec\nneural speech codec and their potential for low-latency speech processing. Through\nprobing analyses, we showed that the TIRE module primarily captures global\nacoustic and paralinguistic information while retaining little linguistic content.\nWe further demonstrated that the choice of extraction layer and segment selec-\ntion strategy significantly influences the quality and robustness of the learned\ninvariant representations.\n    Building on these observations, we proposed Dual-TIRE, a multi-level ar-\nchitecture that exploits the complementarity of invariant representations ex-\ntracted from different encoder layers. Experimental results on both in-domain\nand out-of-domain datasets showed consistent improvements in speech quality\nand speaker similarity compared to the original TiCodec architecture.\n    Finally, we evaluated TiCodec in a streaming inference setting based on suc-\ncessive 660 ms processing blocks. The results indicate that streaming operation\ncan be achieved with only minor performance degradation, confirming that fac-\ntorized neural codec representations constitute a promising direction for future\nlow-latency speech generation systems.\n\n\nAcknowledgement\nThis work was supported by 2022 Jelinek Memorial Summer Workshop on\nSpeech and Language Technologies at BUT@Brno. This project has also received\nfunding from the European Union’s Horizon 2020 research and innovation pro-\ngramme under the Marie Sklodowska-Curie grant agreement No 101007666. This\nwork was performed using HPC resources from GENCI–IDRIS (AD011012551R4\nand AD011012108R3).\n\n\nReferences\n 1. N. Zeghidour, A. Luebs, A. Omran, J. Skoglund, and M. Tagliasacchi, “Sound-\n    stream: An end-to-end neural audio codec,” IEEE/ACM Transactions on Audio,\n    Speech, and Language Processing, vol. 30, pp. 495–507, 2021.\n 2. A. Défossez, J. Copet, G. Synnaeve, and Y. Adi, “High fidelity neural audio\n    compression,” 2022. [Online]. Available: https://arxiv.org/abs/2210.13438\n 3. R. Kumar, P. Seetharaman, A. Luebs, I. Kumar, and K. Kumar, “High-fidelity\n    audio compression with improved rvqgan,” Advances in Neural Information Pro-\n    cessing Systems, vol. 36, pp. 27 980–27 993, 2023.\n 4. Z. Borsos, R. Marinier, D. Vincent, E. Kharitonov, O. Pietquin, M. Sharifi, D. Rob-\n    lek, O. Teboul, D. Grangier, M. Tagliasacchi et al., “Audiolm: a language modeling\n    approach to audio generation,” IEEE/ACM transactions on audio, speech, and lan-\n    guage processing, vol. 31, pp. 2523–2533, 2023.\n 5. E. Kharitonov, A. Lee, A. Polyak, Y. Adi, J. Copet, K. Lakhotia, T.-A. Nguyen,\n    M. Riviere, A. Mohamed, E. Dupoux et al., “Text-free prosody-aware generative\n    spoken language modeling,” in ACL, 2022.\n\f   Streaming Neural Speech Codecs through Time-Invariant Representations             15\n\n 6. C. Wang, S. Chen, Y. Wu, Z. Zhang, L. Zhou, S. Liu, Z. Chen, Y. Liu, H. Wang,\n    J. Li et al., “Neural codec language models are zero-shot text to speech synthesiz-\n    ers,” arXiv preprint arXiv:2301.02111, 2023.\n 7. M. Le, A. Vyas, B. Shi, B. Karrer, L. Sari, R. Moritz, M. Williamson, V. Manohar,\n    Y. Adi, J. Mahadeokar et al., “Voicebox: Text-guided multilingual universal speech\n    generation at scale,” Advances in neural information processing systems, vol. 36,\n    pp. 14 005–14 034, 2023.\n 8. Z. Ju, Y. Wang, K. Shen, X. Tan, D. Xin, D. Yang, Y. Liu, Y. Leng, K. Song,\n    S. Tang et al., “Naturalspeech 3: zero-shot speech synthesis with factorized codec\n    and diffusion models,” in Proceedings of the 41st International Conference on Ma-\n    chine Learning, 2024, pp. 22 605–22 623.\n 9. Y. Ren, T. Wang, J. Yi, L. Xu, J. Tao, C. Y. Zhang, and J. Zhou, “Fewer-token\n    neural speech codec with time-invariant codes,” in ICASSP. IEEE, 2024, pp.\n    12 737–12 741.\n10. A. Nagrani, J. S. Chung, W. Xie, and A. Zisserman, “Voxceleb: Large-scale speaker\n    verification in the wild,” Computer Speech & Language, vol. 60, p. 101027, 2020.\n11. A. Mesaros, T. Heittola, and T. Virtanen, “A multi-device dataset for urban acous-\n    tic scene classification,” arXiv preprint arXiv:1807.09840, 2018.\n12. S. Poria, D. Hazarika, N. Majumder, G. Naik, E. Cambria, and R. Mihalcea, “Meld:\n    A multimodal multi-party dataset for emotion recognition in conversations,” in\n    ACL, 2019.\n13. R. Ardila, M. Branson, K. Davis, M. Kohler, J. Meyer, M. Henretty, R. Morais,\n    L. Saunders, F. Tyers, and G. Weber, “Common voice: A massively-multilingual\n    speech corpus,” in Proceedings of the twelfth language resources and evaluation\n    conference, 2020, pp. 4218–4222.\n14. P. Warden, “Speech commands: A dataset for limited-vocabulary speech recogni-\n    tion,” arXiv preprint arXiv:1804.03209, 2018.\n15. H. Zen, V. Dang, R. Clark, Y. Zhang, R. J. Weiss, Y. Jia, Z. Chen, and Y. Wu,\n    “Libritts: A corpus derived from librispeech for text-to-speech,” Interspeech, 2019.\n16. V. Panayotov, G. Chen, D. Povey, and S. Khudanpur, “Librispeech: an asr corpus\n    based on public domain audio books,” in 2015 IEEE international conference on\n    acoustics, speech and signal processing (ICASSP). IEEE, 2015, pp. 5206–5210.\n17. C. Veaux, J. Yamagishi, K. MacDonald et al., “Cstr vctk corpus: English multi-\n    speaker corpus for cstr voice cloning toolkit,” University of Edinburgh. The Centre\n    for Speech Technology Research (CSTR), vol. 6, p. 15, 2017.\n18. H. He, Z. Shang, C. Wang, X. Li, Y. Gu, H. Hua, L. Liu, C. Yang, J. Li, P. Shi\n    et al., “Emilia: An extensive, multilingual, and diverse speech dataset for large-\n    scale speech generation,” in Spoken Language Technology Workshop (SLT). IEEE,\n    2024, pp. 885–890.\n19. M. Chinen, F. S. C. Lim, J. Skoglund, N. Gureev, F. O’Gorman, and A. Hines,\n    “Visqol v3: An open source production ready objective speech and audio metric,”\n    2020. [Online]. Available: https://arxiv.org/abs/2004.09584\n20. A. Rix, J. Beerends, M. Hollier, and A. Hekstra, “Perceptual evaluation of speech\n    quality (pesq)-a new method for speech quality assessment of telephone networks\n    and codecs,” in ICASSP, 2001.\n21. C. H. Taal, R. C. Hendriks, R. Heusdens, and J. Jensen, “An algorithm for intel-\n    ligibility prediction of time–frequency weighted noisy speech,” IEEE Transactions\n    on Audio, Speech, and Language Processing, vol. 19, no. 7, pp. 2125–2136, 2011.\n22. R. Kubichek, “Mel-cepstral distance measure for objective speech quality assess-\n    ment,” in Proceedings of IEEE Pacific Rim Conference on Communications Com-\n    puters and Signal Processing, vol. 1, 1993, pp. 125–128 vol.1.\n\f", "numLines": 256, "startLine": 549, "totalLines": 804}}}
